  "prompt": "How is gender determined genetically?",
  "response": "Gender is determined genetically through sex chromosomes:\n\n1. In humans, biological sex is determined by the X and Y chromosomes:\n- Females typically have two X chromosomes (XX)\n- Males typically have one X and one Y chromosome (XY)\n\n2. The Y chromosome contains the SRY gene, which triggers male sexual differentiation:\n- During embryonic development, the SRY gene initiates male gonadal development\n- Without the SRY gene, the embryo develops female reproductive structures\n\n3. During conception, the sex of the offspring is determined by the sperm:\n- Eggs always carry an X chromosome\n- Sperm can carry either an X or Y chromosome\n- The chromosome from the sperm determines the genetic sex of the offspring\n\n4. Variations can occur, such as:\n- XXY (Klinefelter syndrome)\n- XO (Turner syndrome)\n- Chromosomal mosaicism\n\n5. Hormones and environmental factors can also influence sexual development and gender expression, but the initial genetic determination occurs at conception through sex chromosomes.",
